Note:
Runtime timer wheel — the monotonic timer facility of the Runa async runtime.

This module is the time-driven scheduling counterpart to the event loop's
readiness-driven scheduling. Where the event loop wakes callbacks when a file
descriptor becomes ready, this facility wakes callbacks when a point in time
is reached. It owns no file descriptors and no threads; it is a pure registry
of pending timers keyed on an absolute monotonic deadline, plus the small
amount of syscall glue needed to read the clock and to sleep until the next
deadline.

Mechanism: time comes from the OS CLOCK_MONOTONIC clock, reached through the
completed platform syscall facade (clock_gettime / nanosleep). CLOCK_MONOTONIC
is used deliberately — it never runs backward and is unaffected by wall-clock
adjustments (NTP steps, settimeofday, daylight changes), so a deadline
computed as now()+delay always fires after exactly that much elapsed time.
All time inside this module is a single Integer count of nanoseconds, folded
from the kernel's two-field timespec so that deadline arithmetic is plain
integer add/compare with no field juggling on the hot path.

A Timer entry is a permanent-until-fired record of "call this callback when
this deadline is reached". Periodic timers (interval greater than 0) re-arm
themselves after firing; one-shot timers (interval 0) are dropped after their
single firing. The wheel holds a growable array of Timer pointers; the Timer
pointer itself is the caller-visible timer id, so cancel and dispatch never
search on an opaque handle.

RuntimeTimerWheel layout (24 bytes):
    offset 0:   timers    — growable array of Timer pointers (8 bytes each)
    offset 8:   capacity  — number of pointer slots in the timers array
    offset 16:  count     — number of live Timer entries (also active count)

Timer layout (40 bytes):
    offset 0:   deadline_ns — absolute CLOCK_MONOTONIC nanosecond fire time
    offset 8:   interval_ns — re-arm period in ns; 0 marks a one-shot timer
    offset 16:  callback    — the $name function pointer dispatched on expiry
    offset 24:  user_arg    — opaque argument passed to callback
    offset 32:  active      — 1 armed, 0 retired (a defensive liveness flag)

timespec ABI (16 bytes — kernel contract for clock_gettime / nanosleep):
    offset 0:   tv_sec  — whole seconds  (8 bytes)
    offset 8:   tv_nsec — nanoseconds within the second (8 bytes)
    The monotonic nanosecond value this module works in is folded as
    tv_sec * 1000000000 + tv_nsec, and unfolded for nanosleep as
    tv_sec = ns / 1000000000, tv_nsec = ns modulo 1000000000.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/platform/linux_x86_64/syscall.runa" as Sys
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/call_indirect.runa" as Call

Note: RuntimeTimerWheel object layout
Constant WHEEL_SIZE as Integer is 24
Constant WHEEL_OFF_TIMERS as Integer is 0
Constant WHEEL_OFF_CAPACITY as Integer is 8
Constant WHEEL_OFF_COUNT as Integer is 16

Note: Timer object layout
Constant TIMER_STRUCT_SIZE as Integer is 40
Constant TIMER_OFF_DEADLINE as Integer is 0
Constant TIMER_OFF_INTERVAL as Integer is 8
Constant TIMER_OFF_CALLBACK as Integer is 16
Constant TIMER_OFF_USERARG as Integer is 24
Constant TIMER_OFF_ACTIVE as Integer is 32

Note: Size of one pointer slot in the timers array
Constant PTR_SIZE as Integer is 8

Note: Initial number of Timer slots in a fresh wheel
Constant WHEEL_DEFAULT_CAPACITY as Integer is 8

Note: timespec ABI — 16 bytes, two 8-byte fields
Constant TIMESPEC_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant TS_OFF_SEC as Integer is 0
Constant TS_OFF_NSEC as Integer is 8

Note: Nanoseconds per second — the fold/unfold factor for timespec
Constant NS_PER_SEC as Integer is 1000000000

Note: CLOCK_MONOTONIC — never runs backward, immune to wall-clock adjustment
Constant CLOCK_MONOTONIC as Integer is 1

Note: NULL remaining-time pointer for nanosleep (no interrupt bookkeeping)
Constant TIMER_NULL_REM as Integer is 0

Note: Status codes returned by the runtime timer wheel API
Constant TIMER_OK as Integer is 0
Constant TIMER_ERR_NULL as Integer is 0 minus 1
Constant TIMER_ERR_ALLOC as Integer is 0 minus 2

Note: Sentinel returned by timer_next_deadline when no timer is armed
Constant TIMER_NO_DEADLINE as Integer is 0 minus 1

Process called "timer_wheel_new" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Construct an empty timer registry. The wheel is deliberately minimal: a
    growable array of Timer pointers plus its capacity and live count. No clock
    is read and no timer is armed at construction — a fresh wheel simply has
    somewhere to put timers.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate the 24-byte wheel object, then allocate the initial Timer pointer
    array (default capacity slots of 8 bytes each). If either allocation fails,
    unwind anything already acquired and return 0. Initialize count to 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two small allocations on the cold construction path. The pointer array is
    grown by doubling so total copying stays linear across the wheel's lifetime.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Failure returns 0 (NULL); callers MUST check before use.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let wheel be proc allocate from Memory with WHEEL_SIZE
    If wheel is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cap be WHEEL_DEFAULT_CAPACITY
    Let array_bytes be cap multiplied by PTR_SIZE
    Let timers be proc allocate from Memory with array_bytes
    If timers is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with wheel
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_TIMERS, timers
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_CAPACITY, cap
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_COUNT, 0
    Return wheel
End Process

Process called "timer_now" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return the current monotonic time as a single nanosecond count. This is the
    time base every deadline is computed against; using CLOCK_MONOTONIC means
    the value only ever increases and is unaffected by wall-clock changes, so
    interval accounting cannot be corrupted by an NTP step or a manual clock
    set.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate a scratch 16-byte timespec, fill it with clock_gettime on
    CLOCK_MONOTONIC, read tv_sec at offset 0 and tv_nsec at offset 8, and fold
    them to nanoseconds as tv_sec * 1000000000 + tv_nsec. Free the scratch
    timespec before returning. A negative syscall result means the clock read
    failed; in that case the folded value is still computed from whatever the
    kernel left in the buffer, but a well-formed CLOCK_MONOTONIC read never
    fails on a supported kernel.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One clock_gettime syscall plus one scratch allocation. clock_gettime is a
    vDSO-accelerated call on Linux, so it is inexpensive relative to a general
    syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The scratch buffer is private to this call and freed before return, so no
    time value leaks through shared state.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let ts be proc allocate from Memory with TIMESPEC_SIZE
    If ts is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc linux_x86_64_syscall_clock_gettime from Sys with CLOCK_MONOTONIC, ts
    Let secs be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ts, TS_OFF_SEC
    Let nsec be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ts, TS_OFF_NSEC
    proc deallocate from Memory with ts

    Let secs_ns be secs multiplied by NS_PER_SEC
    Let total_ns be secs_ns plus nsec
    Return total_ns
End Process

Process called "timer_add" takes wheel as Integer, delay_ns as Integer, interval_ns as Integer, callback as Integer, user_arg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Arm a new timer. The deadline is captured as an absolute monotonic instant
    (now plus the requested delay) rather than kept as a relative delay, so a
    single now() read at advance time can decide every timer's expiry with a
    plain compare. The returned Timer pointer is the caller-visible id used to
    cancel the timer later, so no separate handle table is needed.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read now() and compute deadline = now + delay_ns. Allocate a 40-byte Timer,
    store deadline, interval, callback, user_arg, and active = 1. Append the
    Timer pointer to the wheel's array, doubling the array first if it is full:
    the new backing store is allocated, existing pointers are copied with
    memory_copy, the old store is freed, and capacity is updated. If the grow
    allocation fails, the just-allocated Timer is freed and 0 is returned so no
    partial state is left. On success the Timer pointer (the id) is returned.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One clock read, one Timer allocation, and an amortized-O(1) array append.
    Doubling growth keeps total copying linear across the wheel's lifetime.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null wheel returns 0. A failed allocation returns 0 and leaks nothing. The
    callback pointer is invoked verbatim later via call_indirect_1, matching
    that primitive's contract — the caller must supply a valid $name pointer.
    @End Security_Scope

    If wheel is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let now_ns be timer_now()
    Let deadline be now_ns plus delay_ns

    Let timer be proc allocate from Memory with TIMER_STRUCT_SIZE
    If timer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with timer, TIMER_OFF_DEADLINE, deadline
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with timer, TIMER_OFF_INTERVAL, interval_ns
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with timer, TIMER_OFF_CALLBACK, callback
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with timer, TIMER_OFF_USERARG, user_arg
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with timer, TIMER_OFF_ACTIVE, 1

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_COUNT
    Let cap be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_CAPACITY
    If count is equal to cap:
        Let new_cap be cap multiplied by 2
        If new_cap is equal to 0:
            Set new_cap to WHEEL_DEFAULT_CAPACITY
        End If
        Let new_bytes be new_cap multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let new_array be proc allocate from Memory with new_bytes
        If new_array is equal to 0:
            proc deallocate from Memory with timer
            Return 0
        End If
        Let old_array be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_TIMERS
        Let copy_bytes be count multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        proc memory_copy from Memory with new_array, old_array, copy_bytes
        proc deallocate from Memory with old_array
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_TIMERS, new_array
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_CAPACITY, new_cap
    End If

    Let array be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_TIMERS
    Let slot_offset be count multiplied by PTR_SIZE
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with array, slot_offset, timer
    Let new_count be count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_COUNT, new_count
    Return timer
End Process

Process called "timer_cancel" takes wheel as Integer, timer_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Retire a timer before it fires. Cancellation must keep the timers array
    dense so the live count stays accurate and future scans stay cheap, and it
    must reclaim the Timer object so a cancelled timer leaks nothing.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Linearly locate the array index holding timer_id (the timer set is small
    and walked rarely). Mark the Timer inactive, then compact the array by
    moving the last pointer into the vacated slot (a no-op when the cancelled
    entry was already last), decrement count, and free the Timer. A timer_id
    not present is reported as TIMER_ERR_NULL rather than silently ignored.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One linear scan, an O(1) swap-compaction, and one deallocate. No array
    shrink — capacity is retained for reuse.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null wheel returns TIMER_ERR_NULL. Cancelling an unknown id returns
    TIMER_ERR_NULL without altering any state. After cancel the timer_id
    pointer is dangling and must not be reused.
    @End Security_Scope

    If wheel is equal to 0:
        Return TIMER_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_COUNT
    Let array be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_TIMERS
    Let idx be 0 minus 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let slot_offset be i multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let candidate be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with array, slot_offset
        If candidate is equal to timer_id:
            Set idx to i
            Set i to count
        Otherwise:
            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
    End While

    If idx is less than 0:
        Return TIMER_ERR_NULL
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with timer_id, TIMER_OFF_ACTIVE, 0

    Let last_idx be count minus 1
    If idx is not equal to last_idx:
        Let idx_offset be idx multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let last_offset be last_idx multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let moved be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with array, last_offset
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with array, idx_offset, moved
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_COUNT, last_idx
    proc deallocate from Memory with timer_id
    Return TIMER_OK
End Process

Process called "timer_advance" takes wheel as Integer, now_ns as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Fire every timer whose deadline has been reached at the supplied monotonic
    instant. Passing now_ns in (rather than reading the clock here) lets a
    driver read the clock once and advance several wheels against the same
    instant, and makes the firing behaviour deterministic under test.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Walk the live timers. For each timer whose deadline is at or before now_ns,
    invoke its callback via call_indirect_1(callback, user_arg) exactly once and
    count the firing. A periodic timer (interval greater than 0) is then
    re-armed by advancing its deadline by whole intervals until it is strictly
    after now_ns — this catches up across an arbitrary number of missed periods
    in one step so a badly-overdue periodic timer fires once here instead of
    busy-looping through every elapsed period. A one-shot timer (interval 0) is
    removed by swap-compaction and freed. Because a fired one-shot leaves a new
    (previously-last) entry in the current slot, the index is not advanced after
    a removal so that swapped-in entry is examined; the index advances only when
    a timer is kept (re-armed or not yet due). The wheel's array pointer and
    count are re-read each turn because a fired callback may itself add timers
    and grow (reallocate) the array. Returns the number of callbacks fired.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One pass over the live timers, one indirect call per fired timer, and an
    O(1) removal per expired one-shot. Periodic catch-up is a short integer
    loop bounded by the number of missed periods, executed once per advance.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null wheel returns TIMER_ERR_NULL (distinguishable from any non-negative
    fire count). Callbacks are dispatched synchronously in array order; a
    callback must not cancel or destroy this wheel during the advance, as the
    surrounding scan holds positional state — it may, however, safely add new
    timers, whose deadlines are honoured on a subsequent advance.
    @End Security_Scope

    If wheel is equal to 0:
        Return TIMER_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let fired be 0
    Let i be 0
    Let scanning be 1
    While scanning is equal to 1:
        Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_COUNT
        If i is less than count:
            Let array be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_TIMERS
            Let slot_offset be i multiplied by PTR_SIZE
            Let timer be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with array, slot_offset
            Let deadline be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with timer, TIMER_OFF_DEADLINE
            If deadline is less than or equal to now_ns:
                Let callback be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with timer, TIMER_OFF_CALLBACK
                Let user_arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with timer, TIMER_OFF_USERARG
                If callback is not equal to 0:
                    proc call_indirect_1 from Call with callback, user_arg
                End If
                Set fired to fired plus 1

                Let interval be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with timer, TIMER_OFF_INTERVAL
                If interval is greater than 0:
                    Let next_deadline be deadline plus interval
                    Let catching_up be 1
                    While catching_up is equal to 1:
                        If next_deadline is less than or equal to now_ns:
                            Set next_deadline to next_deadline plus interval
                        Otherwise:
                            Set catching_up to 0
                        End If
                    End While
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with timer, TIMER_OFF_DEADLINE, next_deadline
                    Set i to i plus 1
                Otherwise:
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with timer, TIMER_OFF_ACTIVE, 0
                    Let cur_array be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_TIMERS
                    Let cur_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_COUNT
                    Let last_idx be cur_count minus 1
                    If i is not equal to last_idx:
                        Let i_offset be i multiplied by PTR_SIZE
                        Let last_offset be last_idx multiplied by PTR_SIZE
                        Let moved be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur_array, last_offset
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with cur_array, i_offset, moved
                    End If
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_COUNT, last_idx
                    proc deallocate from Memory with timer
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Set i to i plus 1
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Set scanning to 0
        End If
    End While
    Return fired
End Process

Process called "timer_next_deadline" takes wheel as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report the earliest absolute deadline among all armed timers, which is the
    instant a driver must sleep until to service the wheel with no busy-waiting
    and no premature wake.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Scan the live timers tracking the minimum deadline seen. A found flag
    distinguishes "no timers armed" from a legitimate deadline value (a deadline
    can in principle be any non-negative nanosecond count), so an empty wheel is
    reported as TIMER_NO_DEADLINE (0 minus 1) rather than a spurious 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One linear scan over the live timers with two integer compares per entry.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null wheel returns TIMER_NO_DEADLINE. Pure read; no state is modified.
    @End Security_Scope

    If wheel is equal to 0:
        Return TIMER_NO_DEADLINE
    End If

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_COUNT
    Let array be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_TIMERS
    Let found be 0
    Let best be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let slot_offset be i multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let timer be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with array, slot_offset
        Let deadline be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with timer, TIMER_OFF_DEADLINE
        If found is equal to 0:
            Set best to deadline
            Set found to 1
        Otherwise:
            If deadline is less than best:
                Set best to deadline
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If found is equal to 0:
        Return TIMER_NO_DEADLINE
    End If
    Return best
End Process

Process called "timer_sleep_until_next" takes wheel as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Block the calling thread until the next timer is due, so a single-threaded
    timer driver can idle in the kernel between deadlines instead of polling.
    Sleeping to an absolute deadline (rather than a fixed delay) means the wake
    lands on the timer's due instant regardless of how long the caller spent
    elsewhere before calling this.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the next deadline; if none is armed there is nothing to wait for and
    TIMER_OK is returned immediately. Otherwise compute the remaining span as
    next_deadline minus now(). A non-positive span means the timer is already
    due, so no sleep is performed. A positive span is unfolded into a timespec
    (tv_sec = span / 1000000000, tv_nsec = span modulo 1000000000) on a scratch
    allocation and passed to nanosleep with a NULL remaining-time pointer; the
    scratch timespec is freed afterward. TIMER_OK is returned in all
    non-null-wheel cases.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    At most one nanosleep syscall and one scratch allocation. When a timer is
    already due the call returns after two clock-relative integer operations
    with no syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null wheel returns TIMER_ERR_NULL. nanosleep may return early if the thread
    receives a signal; callers that require the full span to elapse should
    re-check timer_next_deadline and sleep again, as the wake is edge- rather
    than level-triggered.
    @End Security_Scope

    If wheel is equal to 0:
        Return TIMER_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let next_deadline be timer_next_deadline(wheel)
    If next_deadline is less than 0:
        Return TIMER_OK
    End If

    Let now_ns be timer_now()
    Let span be next_deadline minus now_ns
    If span is less than or equal to 0:
        Return TIMER_OK
    End If

    Let ts be proc allocate from Memory with TIMESPEC_SIZE
    If ts is equal to 0:
        Return TIMER_ERR_ALLOC
    End If
    Let secs be span divided by NS_PER_SEC
    Let nsec be span modulo NS_PER_SEC
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ts, TS_OFF_SEC, secs
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ts, TS_OFF_NSEC, nsec
    proc linux_x86_64_syscall_nanosleep from Sys with ts, TIMER_NULL_REM
    proc deallocate from Memory with ts
    Return TIMER_OK
End Process

Process called "timer_count" takes wheel as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report how many timers are currently armed, which is the figure that decides
    whether a timer driver has any work left to schedule.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Return the count field, which timer_add (increment), timer_cancel
    (decrement with compaction), and timer_advance (decrement per fired
    one-shot) keep exactly equal to the number of live Timer entries.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null wheel returns 0. Pure read.
    @End Security_Scope

    If wheel is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_COUNT
End Process

Process called "timer_destroy" takes wheel as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Fully tear down a wheel with no leaks: every armed Timer is freed, then the
    pointer array and the wheel object are released. This is why the wheel keeps
    the array — without it the per-timer objects could not be reclaimed.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Walk the timers array freeing each live Timer, then free the array backing
    store and finally the wheel object itself.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One deallocate per live timer, then two more deallocates. Cold path: done
    once per wheel.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null wheel returns TIMER_ERR_NULL. After destroy the wheel pointer is
    dangling and must not be reused.
    @End Security_Scope

    If wheel is equal to 0:
        Return TIMER_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let array be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_TIMERS
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with wheel, WHEEL_OFF_COUNT
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let slot_offset be i multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let timer be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with array, slot_offset
        If timer is not equal to 0:
            proc deallocate from Memory with timer
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc deallocate from Memory with array
    proc deallocate from Memory with wheel
    Return TIMER_OK
End Process
